## Pattern

👉 Frequency Counting + Heap

---

## Recognition Trigger

Look for:

```text id="tkf1"
Top K frequent
Most common
K most frequent
Highest frequency
```

Think:

```text id="tkf2"
Hash Map + Heap
```

---

# Key Insight

The problem is really two subproblems:

### Step 1

Count frequencies

```text id="tkf3"
1 -> 3 times
2 -> 2 times
3 -> 1 time
```

Use:

```cpp id="tkf4"
unordered_map<int,int>
```

(or map, as you did)

---

### Step 2

Find the largest frequencies

That's exactly what a heap is good at.

Store:

```cpp id="tkf5"
{frequency, value}
```

inside a max heap.

---

# Your Solution

### Frequency Count

```cpp id="tkf6"
map<int,int> freq;

for (int x : nums)
    freq[x]++;
```

Example:

```text id="tkf7"
nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3]

freq:

1 -> 3
2 -> 2
3 -> 1
```

---

### Heap Construction

```cpp id="tkf8"
priority_queue<pair<int,int>> pq;
```

Store:

```text id="tkf9"
(3,1)
(2,2)
(1,3)
```

Heap automatically orders by:

```text id="tkf10"
frequency first
```

because frequency is the first element of the pair.

---

### Extract Top K

```cpp id="tkf11"
while (k--) {
    res.push_back(pq.top().second);
    pq.pop();
}
```

Gets:

```text id="tkf12"
highest frequency elements
```

---

# Complexity

### Frequency counting

```text id="tkf13"
O(n)
```

with unordered_map

Your map version:

```text id="tkf14"
O(n log n)
```

---

### Heap insertion

If there are `m` unique numbers:

```text id="tkf15"
O(m log m)
```

---

### Extract K

```text id="tkf16"
O(k log m)
```

---

Overall:

Using `map`

```text id="tkf17"
O(n log n)
```

Using `unordered_map`

```text id="tkf18"
O(n + m log m)
```

---

# Small Improvement

Instead of:

```cpp id="tkf19"
map<int,int>
```

prefer:

```cpp id="tkf20"
unordered_map<int,int>
```

because ordering of keys doesn't matter.

---

# Even Better Solution

The famous optimal solution is:

```text id="tkf21"
Bucket Sort
```

Because:

```text id="tkf22"
frequency <= n
```

You can group numbers by frequency.

Complexity:

```text id="tkf23"
O(n)
```

But for interviews:

```text id="tkf24"
Hash Map + Heap
```

is usually accepted and easier to explain.

